## What needs to change

### Per-item notifications (not batched)

When A arrives: one Discord message for A with its own [Expedite] button.
When B arrives: a separate Discord message for B with its own [Expedite] button.

Each button's `customId` encodes the specific filename: `research_expedite:<basename>`.

---

### New frontmatter status: `expedited`

The cleanest way to express per-item intent is via the frontmatter itself — it's already the source of truth for item state, it persists across restarts, and it's visible in Obsidian.

```yaml
status: expedited   # → run immediately regardless of quiet hours
status: pending     # → run only when gate is clear
```

Button handler updates the item's frontmatter `pending → expedited` via a new `expediteItem(filename)` function exported from `inbox-watcher.js`.

---

### Gate logic moves inside `scanInbox`, not around it

The previous design wrapped `scanInbox` entirely. That can't support per-item bypass. Instead, `scanInbox` always runs, but internally splits items by status:

```js
async function scanInbox() {
  const expedited = findItems('expedited');
  const pending   = findItems('pending');

  // Expedited items always run regardless of gate
  for (const item of expedited) await processFile(item);

  // Pending items respect the gate
  const gateReason = researchGateReason();
  if (gateReason) {
    const newItems = pending.filter(f => !isItemNotified(f));
    if (newItems.length > 0) {
      newItems.forEach(markItemNotified);
      for (const item of newItems) await notifyQuietHoursItem(item);
    }
    return;
  }

  clearNotifiedItems();
  for (const item of pending) await processFile(item);
}
```

`pollAll` no longer needs a gate check — it always calls `withGlobalLock('inbox', scanInbox)`.

